Cell.Data: The population basis specifies the type of elements in the population. For a subject-based measure, this would be boolean (because the population criteria define yes/no values for each individual subject). For a non-subject-based measure, this would be the type of elements in the population (such as encounters or procedures)

A measure specification needs to be able to specify the expected result type of each population criteria. This value SHALL be consistent with the result type of all population-level criteria in the measure
In Health Quality Measure Format, this was referred to as the Item Count metadata attribute
Specifies the term being defined in a definition element
A measure specification must be able to provide definitions for terms that are used to help communicate the measure intent
Specifies whether the related artifact is defining a primary citation for the measure (i.e. one that should appear in the narrative for the measure specification
A measure author must be able to control which citations are the primary source material for the measure specification
Specifies additional guidance for determining how the allocation for the measure specification should be performed
A measure author must be able to provide guidance about the expected allocation for the measure calculation
Specifies which population criteria is the input to an observation definition, or the initial population for a ratio numerator or denominator

For measure observations, the definition must be able to specify which criteria is the input to the measure observation. For ratio numerator and denominator, the definition must be able to specify which initial population to use
Specifies which method to be used to aggregate the measure observation values
For continuous variable measures, the measure observation definition needs to be able to specify how the observations should be aggregated
